03911nam a22004935i 9780674247079DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20202020mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742470797 a10.4159/97806742470792doi  a(DE-B1597)549787  a(OCoLC)1153076014  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aBF575 7aSCI0890002bisacsh1 aDanckert, James, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOut of My Skull :bThe Psychology of Boredom /cJohn D. Eastwood, James Danckert. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. Boredom by Any Other Name -- t2. A Goldilocks World -- t3. The Motivation to Change -- t4. Across the Life Span -- t5. A Consequential Experience -- t6. Boredom at the Extremes -- t7. The Search for Meaning -- t8. An Epidemic in the Making -- t9. Just Go with the Flow -- tCONCLUSION -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tILLUSTRATION CREDITS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNo one likes to be bored. Two leading psychologists explain what causes boredom and how to listen to what it is telling you, so you can live a more engaged life. We avoid boredom at all costs. It makes us feel restless and agitated. Desperate for something to do, we play games on our phones, retie our shoes, or even count ceiling tiles. And if we escape it this time, eventually it will strike again. But what if we listened to boredom instead of banishing it? Psychologists James Danckert and John Eastwood contend that boredom isn’t bad for us. It’s just that we do a bad job of heeding its guidance. When we’re bored, our minds are telling us that whatever we are doing isn’t working—we’re failing to satisfy our basic psychological need to be engaged and effective. Too many of us respond poorly. We become prone to accidents, risky activities, loneliness, and ennui, and we waste ever more time on technological distractions. But, Danckert and Eastwood argue, we can let boredom have the opposite effect, motivating the change we need. The latest research suggests that an adaptive approach to boredom will help us avoid its troubling effects and, through its reminder to become aware and involved, might lead us to live fuller lives. Out of My Skull combines scientific findings with everyday observations to explain an experience we’d like to ignore, but from which we have a lot to learn. Boredom evolved to help us. It’s time we gave it a chance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aBoredomxPsychological aspects. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Neuroscience.2bisacsh1 aEastwood, John D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069005740uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067424707940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674247079423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674247079.jpg  a978-3-11-069005-7  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles